  "conclusion": {
    "answer": "not_sufficiently_proven",
    "can_claim": [
      "Bucketized static deployment is semantically viable in principle when padded buckets return last_nonpad logits or use explicit last_token_indices.",
      "At the PyTorch wrapper level, right-padding plus last_nonpad token selection is close to exact-shape execution for the tested routed requests; random padded cases need a looser FP16 tolerance than 1e-2.",
      "For b4_s64 random input, baseline_last, flatten_last, and flatten_last_nonpad_index ONNX Runtime outputs all match PyTorch under atol=6e-2, rtol=1e-2.",
      "Earlier constant-input and static flatten-vs-baseline checks are useful smoke tests, but they are not enough for deployment correctness."
    ],
    "cannot_claim_yet": [
      "The current deployed IREE dynamic and static bucket artifacts are not proven correct.",
      "The b4_s64 random direct IREE matrix failed all four tested routes, including exact b4_s64 -> b4_s64.",
      "The PyTorch diagnosis shows both dynamic IREE and bucket IREE differ from PyTorch references by large margins, while PyTorch dynamic-vs-fixed differences are small by comparison.",
      "The static b4_s64 baseline/flatten/last_nonpad_index PyTorch diagnosis now runs, and even baseline_last differs from PyTorch; flatten_last exactly matches baseline_last, so flatten_matmul is not the first source of the large mismatch.",
      "Because ONNX Runtime matches PyTorch but IREE differs from ONNX by large margins, the remaining correctness gap is in IREE import/compile/runtime or IREE parameter loading semantics.",
